"use strict";(self.webpackChunk_N_E=self.webpackChunk_N_E||[]).push([[8874],{88874:function(e){e.exports=JSON.parse('[{"id":"q1","category":"Theory","question":"The Security Layer spec states: \'All inputs validated server-side.\' Why is server-side validation necessary even when you have thorough client-side validation in JavaScript?","options":["Client-side validation is too slow for complex regex patterns and blocks the main thread","Server-side validation is only required for admin endpoints, not public API routes","Clients are untrusted — any attacker can bypass JavaScript by sending raw HTTP requests with curl, Burp Suite, or a custom script. The server is the only trust boundary. Client-side validation is UX convenience; server-side validation is the actual security control","Client-side validation cannot support Unicode or international character sets"],"correct":2,"explanation":"The spec lists \'Client-side validation only\' as a Common Mistake. Browser validation (HTML5 `required`, JavaScript checks) is trivially bypassed: open DevTools, disable the JS, or send a raw HTTP request with `curl -X POST`. The spec\'s validation stack: (1) HTML5 input constraints for UX, (2) JavaScript validation for immediate feedback, (3) Zod/Joi schema validation on the server as the enforced security boundary. The server must assume every incoming request could be crafted by an adversary.","hint":"Can an attacker send an HTTP request to your API without going through your web page? Can they modify what your JavaScript sends?"},{"id":"q2","category":"Theory","question":"The Security architecture diagram shows a WAF (Web Application Firewall) positioned in front of the load balancer. What category of attacks does the WAF specifically intercept that a network load balancer cannot?","options":["Volumetric DDoS attacks that saturate network bandwidth (Layer 3/4 attacks)","Application-layer attacks (Layer 7) — SQL injection patterns, XSS payloads, OWASP Top 10 signatures — by inspecting and filtering the actual HTTP request headers, paths, and bodies","TLS handshake failures and expired SSL certificate errors","BGP route hijacking and DNS cache poisoning attacks"],"correct":1,"explanation":"The spec documents WAF as part of the defense-in-depth layers: Cloudflare/AWS WAF inspects HTTP content, not just IP/port. A network load balancer sees TCP/IP headers — it cannot distinguish `SELECT * FROM users` in a URL query string from a legitimate request. The WAF has OWASP Top 10 rulesets: SQL injection patterns (`\'OR 1=1--`), XSS vectors (`<script>`), path traversal (`../../etc/passwd`), and malformed headers. The spec places WAF before the load balancer so malicious traffic never reaches the application network.","hint":"A load balancer operates at TCP/IP layer — it sees IP addresses and ports. What additional information does a WAF inspect to detect application-layer attacks?"},{"id":"q3","category":"Practical","question":"This endpoint has a critical OWASP Top 10 vulnerability. Identify it and the correct fix:","code":"app.get(\'/api/users\', async (req, res) => {\\n  const role = req.query.role;  // e.g., \'admin\' or \'student\'\\n  \\n  // Fetch users by role\\n  const result = await db.query(\\n    `SELECT id, name, email FROM users WHERE role = \'${role}\'`\\n  );\\n  \\n  res.json(result.rows);\\n});","codeLanguage":"typescript","options":["Missing CORS header — add `res.header(\'Access-Control-Allow-Origin\', \'*\')`","SQL Injection via string interpolation — an attacker sends `role=admin\' OR \'1\'=\'1` to dump all users. Fix: use parameterized query `db.query(\'SELECT id, name, email FROM users WHERE role = $1\', [role])`","Missing authentication middleware — add `@UseGuards(AuthGuard)` before the handler","The response should sanitize email addresses to prevent PII leakage via the API"],"correct":1,"explanation":"The spec lists \'Injection\' as OWASP Top 10 #3 and shows the parameterized query fix: `WHERE id = $1` with data as a separate argument. String interpolation allows `role = admin\' UNION SELECT password, salt, \'\' FROM users--` to extract the password table. Parameterized queries treat user input as data, never as SQL syntax — the database driver escapes it before execution. The spec mandates: \'Parameterized queries (no string interpolation)\' and \'All inputs validated server-side.\'","hint":"What happens if `role` contains a single quote and SQL keywords? Can user input change the structure of the SQL query?"},{"id":"q4","category":"Practical","question":"Your application uses `SameSite=Strict` cookies for session management. A user clicks a link to your app from an email client. What happens to their session?","options":["SameSite=Strict cookies are sent normally — it only blocks POST requests from external origins","SameSite=Strict blocks the session cookie on top-level cross-site navigations from external origins (like email). The user arrives at your site but is logged out — their valid session cookie is not sent. They must navigate directly or bookmark your site to stay logged in","The email client automatically negotiates SameSite=Lax for link-following navigations","SameSite=Strict only blocks embedded iframes and third-party widgets, not top-level navigation"],"correct":1,"explanation":"The spec documents SameSite cookie behavior in the CSRF prevention section. SameSite=Strict means: the cookie is sent ONLY when the request origin matches the cookie domain exactly. An email link makes the browser navigate from a different origin (email client or mail.google.com) — Strict blocks the cookie. SameSite=Lax (the spec\'s recommended balance): cookies are sent on top-level GET navigations from external origins (email links work) but blocked on cross-origin POST/PUT/PATCH requests (CSRF protection maintained).","hint":"SameSite=Strict blocks cookies on ALL cross-site requests — including top-level navigation from an email link. Is this the right tradeoff for most apps?"},{"id":"q5","category":"Theory","question":"According to the Security Production Checklist, what HSTS header value is required and which two directives make it most effective for production?","options":["`max-age=3600` (1 hour) with the `secure` attribute — short TTL for easier rollback","`max-age=86400` (1 day) with `HttpOnly` directive — balances security and deployability","`max-age=31536000` (1 year) with `includeSubDomains; preload` — forces HTTPS for all connections for a full year and enables browser preload list submission so Chrome/Firefox enforce HTTPS before the first connection","`max-age=604800` (1 week) with `SameSite=strict` — weekly rotation prevents HSTS pinning attacks"],"correct":2,"explanation":"The spec explicitly sets HSTS `max-age=31536000` (1 year). HSTS tells browsers: \'never connect to this domain over HTTP for the next year.\' `includeSubDomains` extends this to all subdomains (preventing MITM on api.yourdomain.com). `preload` allows submitting to the browser preload list — browsers enforce HTTPS even on the VERY FIRST visit before any HSTS header is received, eliminating the bootstrap vulnerability. The spec also lists \'HTTPS everywhere\' and \'Security headers (CSP, X-Frame-Options, X-Content-Type-Options)\' as checklist items.","hint":"A 1-hour max-age means HSTS protection expires hourly — what does a 1-year value provide that a short TTL cannot?"}]')}}]);